column11:
  We prove among other things that the omega-limit set of a bounded solution of
a Hamilton system \[\left\{\begin{aligned}
  & \mathbf{\dot{p}}=\frac{\partial H}{\partial \mathbf{q}}
  & \mathbf{\dot{q}}=-\frac{\partial H}{\partial \mathbf{p}} \\ \end{aligned}
\right.\] is containing a full-time solution so there are the limits of $\frac
1t\int_0^t {\mathbf p}(s)ds$ and $\frac 1t\int_0^t {\mathbf q}(s)ds$ as
$t\to\infty$ for any bounded solution $(\mathbf {p,q})$ of the Hamilton system.
These limits are stationary points of the Hamilton system so if a Hamilton
system has no stationary point then every solution of this system is unbounded.
